1
00:00:04,704 --> 00:00:08,538
[Instrumental music plays]

2
00:00:33,666 --> 00:00:36,499
[Propellers whirring]

3
00:02:05,825 --> 00:02:08,453
This is almost a day behind us.

4
00:02:09,996 --> 00:02:11,486
Well, who are they?

5
00:02:11,564 --> 00:02:13,555
Americans? Brits? Italians?

6
00:02:13,633 --> 00:02:15,225
It doesn't even say.

7
00:02:15,301 --> 00:02:18,566
Well, I think we can assume
they're friendly, Mr. Loomis.

8
00:02:22,575 --> 00:02:25,567
Besides, it doesn't appear
to be a suggestion, does it?

9
00:02:31,184 --> 00:02:33,118
What the hell?

10
00:02:33,186 --> 00:02:37,145
Might get a Silver Star
out of this patrol yet.

11
00:02:37,223 --> 00:02:39,316
Just have Coors plot it out.

12
00:03:14,093 --> 00:03:16,288
[Indistinct conversation
in distance]

13
00:03:21,134 --> 00:03:23,398
[Exhales deeply]
Gunners mate standing by, sir.

14
00:03:23,469 --> 00:03:25,801
Stow the weapons.
They're British.

15
00:03:27,140 --> 00:03:29,904
- You can tell that from here?
- It's the sail.

16
00:03:29,976 --> 00:03:32,410
The krauts use white on their
lifeboats. The Brits use red.

17
00:03:32,478 --> 00:03:34,912
Don't they teach you that
in OCS, ensign?

18
00:03:34,981 --> 00:03:38,041
Afraid not, but I can recite
the submariners' motto in Latin.

19
00:03:41,453 --> 00:03:44,422
MAN: Radar contact... starboard
beam, seven miles out, sir.

20
00:03:44,490 --> 00:03:46,651
God damn it!

21
00:03:50,963 --> 00:03:52,055
What if they see us?

22
00:03:52,131 --> 00:03:54,565
Well, they're pouring on
the coal for somebody.

23
00:03:54,633 --> 00:03:57,329
[Indistinct shouting
in distance]

24
00:03:57,403 --> 00:03:58,665
All ahead... emergency.
Rudder to midship.

25
00:03:58,737 --> 00:03:59,669
Crew to battle stations.

26
00:03:59,738 --> 00:04:01,171
All ahead... emergency.
Rudder to midship.

27
00:04:01,240 --> 00:04:02,673
All crew to battle stations.

28
00:04:02,741 --> 00:04:05,335
All right,
do this at flank speed!

29
00:04:05,411 --> 00:04:07,504
I want you to grab
what's breathing on that boat

30
00:04:07,579 --> 00:04:10,309
and you leave
everything else behind!

31
00:04:13,552 --> 00:04:15,486
Stand by to board survivors.

32
00:04:15,554 --> 00:04:17,715
I got him! I got him!

33
00:04:17,790 --> 00:04:19,849
Wounded coming down.

34
00:04:19,925 --> 00:04:21,153
Next man, let's go.

35
00:04:21,226 --> 00:04:22,158
MAN: Come on!

36
00:04:22,227 --> 00:04:24,024
There's a warship approaching,
guys.

37
00:04:24,096 --> 00:04:27,259
Let's move! Move!
Introductions later!

38
00:04:27,332 --> 00:04:29,323
[British accent]
Ow! Ow! I'm going, okay?!

39
00:04:29,401 --> 00:04:31,926
Next man. Next m...

40
00:04:33,272 --> 00:04:35,763
[Panting]

41
00:04:41,113 --> 00:04:43,377
What have we here?

42
00:04:51,390 --> 00:04:53,324
Let's pull the plug.

43
00:04:53,392 --> 00:04:55,952
- [Klaxon blaring]
- Periscope depth.

44
00:04:56,028 --> 00:04:57,620
Periscope depth,
make your depth 65 feet.

45
00:04:57,696 --> 00:04:59,561
Make depth 6-5 feet.

46
00:05:07,105 --> 00:05:09,403
[Whirring]

47
00:05:22,988 --> 00:05:24,421
MAN: Bleed air in the boat.

48
00:05:24,490 --> 00:05:25,718
Bleed air in the boat.

49
00:05:25,791 --> 00:05:27,816
All hatches indicate closed.

50
00:05:27,893 --> 00:05:29,656
All vents indicate open.

51
00:05:29,728 --> 00:05:31,559
Pressure in the boat.

52
00:05:31,630 --> 00:05:33,257
Pressure in the boat.

53
00:06:01,360 --> 00:06:04,591
It's a two-stacker...

54
00:06:04,663 --> 00:06:07,894
about 3,000 tons.

55
00:06:07,966 --> 00:06:10,901
It's not a friendly.

56
00:06:10,969 --> 00:06:12,800
Possible Z-class.

57
00:06:14,506 --> 00:06:17,737
If it is, rear recs,
no side throwers,

58
00:06:17,809 --> 00:06:19,538
four 5-inch guns,
grapple hooks.

59
00:06:19,611 --> 00:06:20,873
Fast screws, Mr. Brice.

60
00:06:20,946 --> 00:06:22,777
30 knots or better.

61
00:06:25,350 --> 00:06:27,716
2-5-0 feet.

62
00:06:27,786 --> 00:06:29,413
Make it 2-5-0 feet.

63
00:06:29,488 --> 00:06:31,581
- MAN: 2-5-0 feet.
- Hard left rudder.

64
00:06:31,657 --> 00:06:32,589
Hard left rudder.

65
00:06:32,658 --> 00:06:34,387
Live to fight another day.

66
00:06:34,459 --> 00:06:36,450
Smart move.

67
00:06:36,528 --> 00:06:37,790
[Big band music playing]

68
00:06:37,896 --> 00:06:41,127
Three survivors... Brits...
and get this...

69
00:06:41,199 --> 00:06:43,963
one's a woman.

70
00:06:44,035 --> 00:06:44,967
[Spits]

71
00:06:45,036 --> 00:06:48,472
[Indistinct conversations]

72
00:06:48,539 --> 00:06:50,871
Three Brits... one's a skirt.

73
00:06:53,945 --> 00:06:55,776
Three limeys... one's a female.

74
00:06:55,847 --> 00:06:56,779
Hey.

75
00:06:56,848 --> 00:06:58,440
Three Brits... one female.

76
00:06:58,516 --> 00:06:59,949
[Laughs]

77
00:07:00,018 --> 00:07:03,112
[Clicking]

78
00:07:03,187 --> 00:07:04,449
Guys, listen up.

79
00:07:04,522 --> 00:07:06,717
We've got three survivors...
all Brits.

80
00:07:06,791 --> 00:07:08,224
One's a woman, eh?

81
00:07:08,293 --> 00:07:11,729
Hey, look lively.
Woman onboard.

82
00:07:11,796 --> 00:07:15,664
Hey, Hoag, spread the news...
three tea bags,

83
00:07:15,733 --> 00:07:18,497
and I hear one's, uh,
bazooma.

84
00:07:18,569 --> 00:07:20,332
We got ourselves a filly?

85
00:07:20,405 --> 00:07:21,337
[Clicks tongue]

86
00:07:21,406 --> 00:07:22,668
Ohh!

87
00:07:22,740 --> 00:07:26,005
Sweet holy Jesus.

88
00:07:26,077 --> 00:07:27,908
You're gonna wanna hear this.

89
00:07:30,081 --> 00:07:33,676
Hey, boys... here's the news.

90
00:07:33,751 --> 00:07:35,514
Front page...

91
00:07:35,586 --> 00:07:39,886
we got three redcoats,
and guess what.

92
00:07:39,958 --> 00:07:42,051
One of them's a bleeder.

93
00:07:42,126 --> 00:07:45,220
Aw, great.
That's all this boat needs...

94
00:07:45,296 --> 00:07:46,888
another piece of rotten luck.

95
00:07:46,965 --> 00:07:48,899
Yeah, well,
if it means you guys

96
00:07:49,000 --> 00:07:51,093
finally wash the butt squirt
outta your shorts,

97
00:07:51,169 --> 00:07:52,329
I'm all for it.

98
00:07:54,639 --> 00:07:57,733
[Groaning]

99
00:07:57,809 --> 00:08:01,006
So what exactly happened
to your shi...

100
00:08:07,018 --> 00:08:10,010
Um... your ship?

101
00:08:10,088 --> 00:08:11,521
[British accent]
Hospital ship.

102
00:08:11,589 --> 00:08:13,250
We were attacked two nights ago.

103
00:08:13,324 --> 00:08:15,224
Two nights?

104
00:08:15,293 --> 00:08:18,387
I'm... I'm sorry.
My brain's a bit foggy.

105
00:08:18,463 --> 00:08:21,591
Although I'm reasonably sure
my name's Claire Page.

106
00:08:21,666 --> 00:08:24,601
The rest of the details
will emerge, I'm sure.

107
00:08:24,669 --> 00:08:27,536
[Howling]

108
00:08:27,605 --> 00:08:28,867
That's just a whale.

109
00:08:28,940 --> 00:08:30,373
It's okay, really.

110
00:08:30,441 --> 00:08:33,069
The sounds down here
still get to me, too.

111
00:08:33,144 --> 00:08:35,704
MAN: Make a hole.
Comin' through. Make a hole.

112
00:08:37,448 --> 00:08:41,214
Yow.
Mind your pretty toes.

113
00:08:41,285 --> 00:08:43,378
Best-lookin' bad luck
I ever saw.

114
00:08:43,454 --> 00:08:45,046
[Laughs]

115
00:08:47,792 --> 00:08:49,555
Doesn't look good, sir.

116
00:08:49,627 --> 00:08:51,686
Why don't you get
those clothes off of him

117
00:08:51,763 --> 00:08:53,731
and see if you can get
a better look at the wounds?

118
00:08:53,798 --> 00:08:55,197
I can dress the wounds.

119
00:08:55,266 --> 00:08:57,131
Other than that, I think
it's best to leave him be.

120
00:09:00,338 --> 00:09:03,603
Okay. All right.

121
00:09:03,674 --> 00:09:05,574
Maybe I didn't make myself
clear.

122
00:09:05,643 --> 00:09:07,406
I saw it.

123
00:09:07,478 --> 00:09:10,936
It crossed the moon's reflection
just before the explosion.

124
00:09:11,015 --> 00:09:13,313
Yes, it was dark, but I...
I did see it.

125
00:09:13,384 --> 00:09:14,646
It wasn't a mine.

126
00:09:14,719 --> 00:09:16,710
I... It was a U-boat.

127
00:09:18,956 --> 00:09:20,890
[Indistinct voice on P.A.]

128
00:09:20,958 --> 00:09:22,653
What class?

129
00:09:22,727 --> 00:09:24,422
Type 7?

130
00:09:24,495 --> 00:09:28,226
Was it an older boat
or one of their newer ones?

131
00:09:28,299 --> 00:09:29,664
Um...

132
00:09:29,734 --> 00:09:31,326
Like this?
Clean at the bow?

133
00:09:31,402 --> 00:09:32,835
- You know...
- No net cutter?

134
00:09:32,904 --> 00:09:35,134
It was just a couple of seconds.
I really couldn't say for...

135
00:09:35,206 --> 00:09:38,004
So you were... you were on
lookout that night, mister...

136
00:09:38,076 --> 00:09:41,011
Kingsley...
second mate, merchant navy.

137
00:09:41,079 --> 00:09:42,011
Uh, no.

138
00:09:42,080 --> 00:09:44,674
I was on the starboard deck
grabbing a gasper.

139
00:09:45,550 --> 00:09:46,642
Having a cigarette.

140
00:09:46,717 --> 00:09:48,344
And how many aboard your ship?

141
00:09:48,419 --> 00:09:50,353
About 300 patients.

142
00:09:50,421 --> 00:09:53,686
At least that many.

143
00:09:53,758 --> 00:09:55,487
Out of North Africa.

144
00:09:57,161 --> 00:09:59,095
Yeah, plus over 70 hands crew.

145
00:09:59,163 --> 00:10:00,255
So, um...

146
00:10:00,331 --> 00:10:02,231
You said they fired
only one torpedo?

147
00:10:02,300 --> 00:10:03,289
O'Dell...

148
00:10:03,367 --> 00:10:05,028
you better tell sonar we've got
an enemy sub in the area.

149
00:10:05,103 --> 00:10:06,434
Yes, sir.
Just let me finish...

150
00:10:06,504 --> 00:10:07,664
Now. Do it now.

151
00:10:07,738 --> 00:10:08,727
Yes, sir.

152
00:10:11,676 --> 00:10:15,612
I'm... I'm sorry that
we couldn't save more. I...

153
00:10:15,680 --> 00:10:19,707
Now this... the third member
of your party, he's...

154
00:10:19,784 --> 00:10:21,342
One of my patients.

155
00:10:23,020 --> 00:10:24,783
Well, under normal
circumstances,

156
00:10:24,856 --> 00:10:27,791
I'd be able to drop you
at the nearest port in England,

157
00:10:27,859 --> 00:10:30,453
but, uh, it's a 300-mile
detour for us.

158
00:10:30,528 --> 00:10:32,621
So I'm sorry.

159
00:10:32,697 --> 00:10:35,165
It seems as though
we're stuck with each other.

160
00:10:39,437 --> 00:10:42,372
Oh, uh, last thing.

161
00:10:42,440 --> 00:10:45,034
Just try not to fraternize
with the men.

162
00:10:45,109 --> 00:10:46,371
Most of the men are fine,

163
00:10:46,444 --> 00:10:49,174
but some of them get a little
strange about having...

164
00:10:49,247 --> 00:10:52,580
[Chuckles] "Strange"
as in "superstitious"?

165
00:10:52,650 --> 00:10:54,880
As in "strange."

166
00:10:54,952 --> 00:10:57,716
"Suddenly, his heart rolled over
backwards in his chest,

167
00:10:57,788 --> 00:11:02,384
"and he saw this huge,
wretched thing before him.

168
00:11:02,460 --> 00:11:04,985
"Instantly, its mouth widened

169
00:11:05,062 --> 00:11:08,327
"into a terrible
and hungry menace.

170
00:11:08,399 --> 00:11:12,165
Now the malediction
uttered a deep-throated sound."

171
00:11:12,236 --> 00:11:14,500
- Malediction?
- Look it up.

172
00:11:14,572 --> 00:11:17,268
"And its breath stank gloriously

173
00:11:17,341 --> 00:11:21,004
"of rotted carp
and matted gorilla skins.

174
00:11:21,078 --> 00:11:24,673
"Now... it slouched toward him...

175
00:11:24,749 --> 00:11:29,015
"not fast, but slowly...

176
00:11:29,086 --> 00:11:30,519
"slowly...

177
00:11:30,588 --> 00:11:32,613
so very slowly."

178
00:11:32,690 --> 00:11:33,622
[Thud]

179
00:11:33,691 --> 00:11:36,785
Silly boy.
Just the bulkhead shifting.

180
00:11:36,861 --> 00:11:39,455
What'd you think it was?

181
00:11:39,530 --> 00:11:41,430
The malediction?

182
00:11:41,499 --> 00:11:42,625
Wahh!

183
00:11:42,700 --> 00:11:44,634
[Laughter]

184
00:11:45,503 --> 00:11:47,767
What exactly bothers you,
O'Dell?

185
00:11:47,838 --> 00:11:49,135
Well, you have a ship

186
00:11:49,207 --> 00:11:52,438
that's sinking slow enough
to get a few lifeboats off,

187
00:11:52,510 --> 00:11:55,035
but the submarine
only fires one torpedo.

188
00:11:55,112 --> 00:11:56,579
I mean,
that's not textbook tactics.

189
00:11:56,647 --> 00:11:58,615
You fire upon the target
until the target is sunk.

190
00:11:58,683 --> 00:12:00,583
So it was their last torpedo.

191
00:12:00,651 --> 00:12:04,417
Yeah, but...
why not use a deck gun?

192
00:12:04,488 --> 00:12:07,924
O'Dell, isn't this
your first patrol?

193
00:12:07,992 --> 00:12:09,118
My second.

194
00:12:09,193 --> 00:12:10,125
Yeah.

195
00:12:10,194 --> 00:12:11,957
And your first was
a little shakedown run

196
00:12:12,029 --> 00:12:13,018
off the coast of Florida

197
00:12:13,097 --> 00:12:14,826
in one of those old school
boats, right?

198
00:12:14,899 --> 00:12:17,732
I'm just wondering if the story
didn't seem a little off.

199
00:12:17,802 --> 00:12:19,235
I wouldn't worry about it,
champ.

200
00:12:19,303 --> 00:12:21,737
They got here somehow.

201
00:12:21,806 --> 00:12:24,400
- You want coffee?
- Sure.

202
00:12:24,475 --> 00:12:26,409
I take it black.

203
00:12:31,482 --> 00:12:33,712
Tell Broadway
make sure it's hot.

204
00:12:35,419 --> 00:12:39,856
[Page speaking indistinctly]

205
00:12:39,924 --> 00:12:41,516
[Man groaning]

206
00:12:41,592 --> 00:12:42,854
PAGE: Try to sleep.

207
00:12:42,927 --> 00:12:45,691
I know you're in pain,
but you must try.

208
00:12:45,763 --> 00:12:48,596
Please.

209
00:12:48,666 --> 00:12:50,156
Be quiet.

210
00:12:59,075 --> 00:13:00,736
[Loud snapping]

211
00:13:12,322 --> 00:13:13,789
Sonar contact.

212
00:13:13,857 --> 00:13:16,951
[Ticking]

213
00:13:17,027 --> 00:13:20,622
220 turns per minute,
Mr. Brice.

214
00:13:20,697 --> 00:13:22,665
Maybe the Z-class.

215
00:13:22,732 --> 00:13:24,723
Maybe we didn't shake him
after all.

216
00:13:32,876 --> 00:13:35,140
[Rumbling]

217
00:13:54,664 --> 00:13:56,655
- Full stop!
- Full stop!

218
00:13:59,102 --> 00:14:02,265
[Whirring, engines slow]

219
00:14:07,010 --> 00:14:07,999
Boat stands at full stop.

220
00:14:08,078 --> 00:14:10,842
[Engines stop, silence]

221
00:14:10,914 --> 00:14:13,007
[Rattling]

222
00:14:13,083 --> 00:14:14,880
[Clicks, silence]

223
00:14:17,187 --> 00:14:19,951
Mr. Coors...

224
00:14:20,023 --> 00:14:21,513
- flood negative.
- Flood negative.

225
00:14:21,591 --> 00:14:25,083
O'Dell, get on the thermograph.
Find us some cold.

226
00:14:37,374 --> 00:14:38,966
[Squeaking]

227
00:14:39,042 --> 00:14:43,536
Conn, 5-degree gradient
at 2-7-0 feet.

228
00:14:47,450 --> 00:14:52,217
Cold water deflects sound waves
just in case they decide to...

229
00:14:52,289 --> 00:14:53,984
- [Sonar pinging]
- Aah!

230
00:14:55,325 --> 00:14:58,158
[Pinging continues]

231
00:15:20,350 --> 00:15:22,341
[Pinging stops]

232
00:15:44,574 --> 00:15:49,011
[Benny Goodman's "Sing, Sing,
Sing (With a Swing)" plays]

233
00:15:56,620 --> 00:15:57,678
[Screeches, stops]

234
00:16:12,569 --> 00:16:14,059
Splashes!

235
00:16:14,137 --> 00:16:15,229
- Splashes!
- Splashes!

236
00:16:31,154 --> 00:16:32,678
[Explosions]

237
00:16:35,125 --> 00:16:38,652
[Explosions continue,
indistinct screaming]

238
00:16:49,439 --> 00:16:52,931
[Electricity crackling,
screaming continues]

239
00:17:01,651 --> 00:17:03,744
MAN: God damn it!
Keep it steady!

240
00:17:03,820 --> 00:17:06,687
[Explosions continue]

241
00:17:12,495 --> 00:17:15,123
[Screaming continues]

242
00:17:29,979 --> 00:17:32,971
[Rattling, all groaning]

243
00:17:38,221 --> 00:17:39,552
[Thud]

244
00:17:41,257 --> 00:17:43,248
[Thudding]

245
00:18:17,660 --> 00:18:19,491
[Thudding stops]

246
00:18:20,530 --> 00:18:23,294
Scared you, didn't it, kid?
[Chuckles]

247
00:18:23,366 --> 00:18:25,197
- [Light bulb shatters]
- [Both scream]

248
00:18:33,276 --> 00:18:35,210
[Sighs]

249
00:18:35,278 --> 00:18:36,939
Damage reports.

250
00:18:37,013 --> 00:18:38,273
[Indistinct conversations]

251
00:18:38,347 --> 00:18:41,248
Well, maybe that Z-class
just happened to be there.

252
00:18:41,317 --> 00:18:43,478
And maybe the phonograph
wasn't secured.

253
00:18:43,552 --> 00:18:44,780
But God damn.

254
00:18:44,854 --> 00:18:47,823
And maybe someone doesn't
want us to make it home.

255
00:18:47,890 --> 00:18:50,450
Miss Page claims she was in
the control room the whole time.

256
00:18:50,526 --> 00:18:51,823
Yeah, that's right.

257
00:18:51,894 --> 00:18:54,055
- So what about the other guy?
- Kingsley?

258
00:18:54,130 --> 00:18:55,461
Hmph!
If that's his name.

259
00:18:55,531 --> 00:18:57,123
Where was he
when it all happened?

260
00:18:57,199 --> 00:19:00,293
I'm not sure.
Maybe he stepped out.

261
00:19:00,369 --> 00:19:01,996
