thank you.

780
00:55:13,072 --> 00:55:16,303
Mr. Brice, both our periscopes
are down, our sonar is gone.

781
00:55:16,375 --> 00:55:18,536
We are blind and nearly deaf.

782
00:55:18,611 --> 00:55:19,543
Our men are in a bad way,

783
00:55:19,612 --> 00:55:21,375
and now we've lost
two of our senior officers.

784
00:55:21,447 --> 00:55:23,005
Welcome to the war, O'Dell.

785
00:55:23,082 --> 00:55:24,845
This has nothing to do
with the war.

786
00:55:24,917 --> 00:55:27,283
Just how much longer
can we not say

787
00:55:27,353 --> 00:55:28,843
what we're all thinking?

788
00:55:32,391 --> 00:55:34,450
No one wants to be the first?

789
00:55:34,527 --> 00:55:36,495
Fine. Allow me.

790
00:55:36,562 --> 00:55:38,291
This submarine is haun...

791
00:55:38,364 --> 00:55:40,958
When I want your opinion,
Miss Page, I'll give it to you.

792
00:55:41,033 --> 00:55:45,026
I am not one of your men that
you can just dismiss, Mr. Brice!

793
00:55:47,006 --> 00:55:49,031
I don't believe
we're alone down here,

794
00:55:49,108 --> 00:55:51,542
and I know some of you think
the same way.

795
00:55:52,378 --> 00:55:54,209
Unless we find
a safe harbor soon,

796
00:55:54,280 --> 00:55:55,304
we're all going to end up like
your friend Mr. Coors.

797
00:55:55,381 --> 00:55:57,645
The loss of Lieutenant Coors
is unfortunate.

798
00:55:57,717 --> 00:56:00,277
It fails to affect our plans.

799
00:56:00,352 --> 00:56:01,785
[Clicks, static]

800
00:56:01,854 --> 00:56:04,618
Attention all hands...
it's daylight now.

801
00:56:04,690 --> 00:56:09,059
I expect to surface... at 1900,

802
00:56:09,128 --> 00:56:10,720
recharge the batteries,

803
00:56:10,796 --> 00:56:13,196
and proceed on base course
back to Connecticut.

804
00:56:13,265 --> 00:56:14,197
- That is all.
- [Switch clicks]

805
00:56:14,266 --> 00:56:15,460
You're 10 seconds away
from finding out

806
00:56:15,534 --> 00:56:17,297
what the penalty is
for mutiny at sea,

807
00:56:17,369 --> 00:56:19,132
'cause that's how long
it's gonna take me

808
00:56:19,205 --> 00:56:21,605
to open the armory
and reload that sidearm.

809
00:56:22,942 --> 00:56:25,672
Now, do either of you
care to say anything else

810
00:56:25,745 --> 00:56:29,442
that might further agitate
this crew or me?

811
00:56:33,018 --> 00:56:34,178
Mr. O'Dell?

812
00:56:40,159 --> 00:56:42,150
Yeah, I didn't think so.

813
00:57:01,280 --> 00:57:03,544
[Sighs]

814
00:57:03,616 --> 00:57:05,208
We just knock the nose around
a little bit,

815
00:57:05,284 --> 00:57:09,220
we're back on base,
so make it 2-8-5.

816
00:57:09,288 --> 00:57:10,380
Make it 2-8-5 true.

817
00:57:10,456 --> 00:57:11,980
2-8-5 true, sir.

818
00:57:14,527 --> 00:57:17,462
[Engines rumbling]

819
00:57:18,531 --> 00:57:20,795
Heading home, boys.
Sound good?

820
00:57:20,866 --> 00:57:22,697
- Yes, sir.
- Sounds good, sir.

821
00:57:23,803 --> 00:57:25,703
[Clanking]

822
00:57:32,478 --> 00:57:35,072
Hey, you're oversteering.
Mind your rudder.

823
00:57:35,147 --> 00:57:36,580
She's getting
some resistance, sir.

824
00:57:37,583 --> 00:57:40,882
[Creaking, rumbling]

825
00:57:49,962 --> 00:57:51,953
[Grunting]

826
00:57:54,633 --> 00:57:55,600
[Rattling]

827
00:57:55,668 --> 00:57:59,570
Chief of boat to control.
Chief of boat to control room.

828
00:57:59,638 --> 00:58:02,903
[Rumbling continues]

829
00:58:06,412 --> 00:58:08,243
[Rumbling continues]

830
00:58:08,314 --> 00:58:10,214
All right, belay that.
Belay that.

831
00:58:12,518 --> 00:58:13,507
I said belay that!

832
00:58:13,586 --> 00:58:15,451
[Explosion]

833
00:58:15,521 --> 00:58:16,249
- Oh!
- Oh!

834
00:58:16,322 --> 00:58:18,187
[Rumbling stops]

835
00:58:20,459 --> 00:58:23,951
[Squeaking]

836
00:58:28,968 --> 00:58:31,402
Rudder at midship, sir.

837
00:58:38,978 --> 00:58:43,039
Um, some...
kind of hydraulic failure.

838
00:58:43,115 --> 00:58:44,707
Oh, Christ.

839
00:58:44,783 --> 00:58:46,273
Must have overshot
our heading by...

840
00:58:46,352 --> 00:58:48,411
170 degrees.

841
00:59:04,703 --> 00:59:07,934
Oh, good. A gun.
Yeah, I needed a gun.

842
00:59:08,007 --> 00:59:10,100
I'll put that
with the prizes.

843
00:59:10,175 --> 00:59:14,771
Okay, I got feathers, crosses,
and strip-show icons...

844
00:59:16,916 --> 00:59:18,508
Rudder malfunction.

845
00:59:18,584 --> 00:59:21,781
When we tried to shut down
the props, no dice.

846
00:59:21,854 --> 00:59:23,412
Wouldn't respond.

847
00:59:23,489 --> 00:59:25,548
We're on a runaway boat,
fellas.

848
00:59:25,624 --> 00:59:27,421
Now, can any of you top that?

849
00:59:27,493 --> 00:59:31,327
[Spits] Well...
I had a strange thought.

850
00:59:31,397 --> 00:59:32,489
Take a number.

851
00:59:32,564 --> 00:59:36,591
Yeah, but this one's
real creep-show stuff.

852
00:59:39,471 --> 00:59:45,410
What if, when we took on
that kraut ship...

853
00:59:45,477 --> 00:59:47,138
...we didn't sink 'em?

854
00:59:48,314 --> 00:59:53,411
What if... they sank us?

855
00:59:53,485 --> 00:59:55,350
Oh, that's a good twist.

856
00:59:58,324 --> 00:59:59,416
I don't get it.

857
00:59:59,491 --> 01:00:03,086
Might explain how that
dead kraut talked to Stumbo.

858
01:00:04,096 --> 01:00:05,188
I don't get it.

859
01:00:05,264 --> 01:00:07,198
And the controls...
that they froze up.

860
01:00:07,266 --> 01:00:08,699
No, they... they rusted up.

861
01:00:08,767 --> 01:00:11,327
That's because we're at the...
the bottom of the ocean.

862
01:00:11,403 --> 01:00:12,335
Flooded out.

863
01:00:12,404 --> 01:00:14,497
Of course, I'm not sure what all
that pounding was about.

864
01:00:14,573 --> 01:00:18,839
Those are rescue divers...
pounding on the hull.

865
01:00:18,911 --> 01:00:20,208
Only it's too late.

866
01:00:20,279 --> 01:00:21,974
Shit, I get it.

867
01:00:22,047 --> 01:00:25,480
Hydrogen from the batteries...

868
01:00:25,550 --> 01:00:29,145
CO2, ozone
from the electrical shorts...

869
01:00:29,220 --> 01:00:31,017
that's what we're breathing
right now.

870
01:00:31,089 --> 01:00:34,024
Like those deep-sea divers
that don't get enough oxygen...

871
01:00:34,092 --> 01:00:36,652
head starts playing tricks
on 'em.

872
01:00:36,728 --> 01:00:40,027
We got mechanical problems,
that's all, okay?

873
01:00:40,098 --> 01:00:41,998
We always got
mechanical problems.

874
01:00:42,066 --> 01:00:44,159
Now, please...

875
01:00:44,235 --> 01:00:47,932
will you pinch this shit off?

876
01:00:48,006 --> 01:00:50,167
- Unless...
- Oh...

877
01:00:50,241 --> 01:00:52,175
It happened
during the depth charging.

878
01:00:52,243 --> 01:00:54,677
Remember that one?

879
01:00:54,746 --> 01:00:57,214
Rolled right down our deck.

880
01:00:57,282 --> 01:00:58,943
[Creaking]

881
01:01:01,519 --> 01:01:04,113
[Clicks]

882
01:01:04,189 --> 01:01:07,454
So exactly how far
from England are we?

883
01:01:07,525 --> 01:01:09,755
Can I ask why you're asking?

884
01:01:09,827 --> 01:01:11,260
No.

885
01:01:11,329 --> 01:01:12,261
Right.

886
01:01:12,330 --> 01:01:14,321
Uh, what's our heading?

887
01:01:14,399 --> 01:01:16,026
0-9-5.

888
01:01:16,100 --> 01:01:19,297
Right. Uh...

889
01:01:19,370 --> 01:01:21,133
[Muttering indistinctly]

890
01:01:21,206 --> 01:01:23,470
May I ask why you're asking?

891
01:01:23,541 --> 01:01:27,136
Just in case the boat
can't make it back home...

892
01:01:27,212 --> 01:01:29,146
for whatever reason.

893
01:01:29,214 --> 01:01:31,808
LOOMIS: What do you suggest
we do about it, chief?

894
01:01:31,883 --> 01:01:33,214
[Indistinct voice]

895
01:01:33,284 --> 01:01:34,876
Come on.
Enough of the guessing games.

896
01:01:34,953 --> 01:01:37,888
- Pressure blinding the shafts.
- No, I don't think that's it.

897
01:01:37,956 --> 01:01:39,389
Just lay it out for us, chief.

898
01:01:39,457 --> 01:01:40,890
What about the I.M.O. pumps?

899
01:01:40,959 --> 01:01:43,792
I.M.O. pumps check out.
I don't think it's that either.

900
01:01:43,861 --> 01:01:46,694
The rudder has a dedicated line
from here to the stern.

901
01:01:46,764 --> 01:01:49,858
If we tap into there
somewhere aft,

902
01:01:49,934 --> 01:01:52,528
I think we should regain
our steering.

903
01:01:52,604 --> 01:01:54,902
But where are you gonna tap in?

904
01:01:54,973 --> 01:01:56,406
That's the thing.

905
01:01:56,474 --> 01:01:59,238
The line goes right through
the battery room.

906
01:01:59,310 --> 01:02:01,505
That's a little dicey, isn't it,
without venting first?

907
01:02:01,579 --> 01:02:04,104
Just threading up
new hydraulics, no welding.

908
01:02:04,182 --> 01:02:05,774
Well, where are we at, anyway?

909
01:02:05,850 --> 01:02:06,782
13 percent down.

910
01:02:06,851 --> 01:02:09,445
- 13 percent hydrogen?
- Keep your voice down.

911
01:02:09,520 --> 01:02:14,116
Look, I don't know any other
way to regain control...

912
01:02:14,192 --> 01:02:16,456
[Rumbling]

913
01:02:16,527 --> 01:02:18,518
[Screeching]

914
01:02:25,436 --> 01:02:27,336
Fuck if I know.

915
01:02:27,405 --> 01:02:30,340
All right, but you gotta
make sure you're sealed off,

916
01:02:30,408 --> 01:02:32,842
'cause we don't want a repeat
of the <i>Hindenburg</i> here.

917
01:02:32,910 --> 01:02:34,400
Let's keep this quiet.

918
01:02:38,416 --> 01:02:42,011
As if it's a bloody
mechanical problem.

919
01:02:42,086 --> 01:02:44,020
[Hinges creak, hatch slams]

920
01:02:44,088 --> 01:02:46,386
[Whirring, clicking]

921
01:03:06,144 --> 01:03:07,873
Fore door sealed.

922
01:03:08,946 --> 01:03:10,345
After door sealed.

923
01:03:39,544 --> 01:03:41,034
[Sighs]

924
01:03:46,351 --> 01:03:48,444
What's happened here, hmm?

925
01:03:48,519 --> 01:03:50,180
What is this?

926
01:03:57,295 --> 01:03:59,695
Go to the galley.
Get a cup of coffee.

927
01:03:59,764 --> 01:04:01,493
Oh, no, I'm fine, sir.
Really.

928
01:04:01,566 --> 01:04:03,329
You're falling asleep, champ.

929
01:04:03,401 --> 01:04:05,631
- I'll watch your bubble.
- Yes, sir.

930
01:04:09,941 --> 01:04:12,372
Lieutenant, a word?

931
01:04:12,442 --> 01:04:13,966
- Not now.
- No, Mr. Loomis.

932
01:04:16,146 --> 01:04:18,478
We need to speak right now.

933
01:04:19,682 --> 01:04:22,242
[Grunts]

934
01:04:23,153 --> 01:04:25,644
[Rumbling]

935
01:04:30,794 --> 01:04:32,921
That is a whale, right?

936
01:04:32,996 --> 01:04:35,931
[Sighs]
What else would it be?

937
01:04:35,999 --> 01:04:37,296
Come on.

938
01:04:37,367 --> 01:04:39,835
Let's get that rudder working.

939
01:04:39,903 --> 01:04:41,666
Now, maybe this is
just a coincidence.

940
01:04:41,738 --> 01:04:43,729
I know Lieutenant Coors
wasn't too sure

941
01:04:43,807 --> 01:04:45,468
about the last star fix.

942
01:04:45,542 --> 01:04:47,134
But it sure seems like
we're going

943
01:04:47,210 --> 01:04:50,702
right back to where
we sunk that German ship.

944
01:04:50,780 --> 01:04:51,974
Clear the compartment.

945
01:04:53,550 --> 01:04:55,484
Everybody, give us 5 minutes.

946
01:04:55,552 --> 01:04:56,712
Go!

947
01:05:00,090 --> 01:05:02,024
All right.
We're almost all set.

948
01:05:02,092 --> 01:05:04,026
Just repressurizing the line,

949
01:05:04,094 --> 01:05:06,460
see if we can't put the brakes
on this little joyride.

950
01:05:06,529 --> 01:05:08,690
[Rumbling, thudding]

951
01:05:10,934 --> 01:05:13,425
[Powers down, silence]

952
01:05:16,506 --> 01:05:19,339
I'll reset the bus.

953
01:05:20,910 --> 01:05:22,878
Shit!

954
01:05:22,946 --> 01:05:24,846
[Whirring]

955
01:05:27,917 --> 01:05:29,111
[Hatch hinges creak]

956
01:05:29,185 --> 01:05:31,517
Hey, guys,
we lost power up here.

957
01:05:31,588 --> 01:05:32,714
Shut that goddamn door

958
01:05:32,789 --> 01:05:36,020
before I shut it
with your goddamn face!

959
01:05:39,929 --> 01:05:41,692
What are you saying, O'Dell?

960
01:05:41,764 --> 01:05:44,232
It's not a coincidence?

961
01:05:45,668 --> 01:05:47,568
Somebody put us on this course?

962
01:05:47,637 --> 01:05:49,571
I'm just asking a question.

963
01:05:49,639 --> 01:05:51,402
Let me ask one.

964
01:05:51,474 --> 01:05:53,567
Where were <i>you</i>
when the rudder went over?

965
01:05:53,643 --> 01:05:55,235
Huh?

966
01:05:55,311 --> 01:05:57,006
This course heads back
to England,

967
01:05:57,080 --> 01:05:59,844
and I've noticed you've had
a hard-on for anything English.

968
01:05:59,916 --> 01:06:01,144
So where were you, O'Dell?

969
01:06:01,217 --> 01:06:03,310
Back of the boat... messing with
the rudder assembly?

970
01:06:03,386 --> 01:06:04,512
Or did you get some motormac...

971
01:06:04,587 --> 01:06:06,316
That is the craziest thing
I have ever heard!

972
01:06:06,389 --> 01:06:07,981
Not as crazy
as what you're saying!

973
01:06:08,057 --> 01:06:10,321
I'm tired
of this hoodoo horseshit!

974
01:06:10,393 --> 01:06:12,156
It is <i>not</i>
what you think it is!

975
01:06:12,228 --> 01:06:14,890
It is not even remotely
<i>fucking</i> possible!

976
01:06:14,964 --> 01:06:16,659
Okay?!

977
01:06:27,277 --> 01:06:28,209
[Clicks]

978
01:06:28,278 --> 01:06:30,838
[Mechanical whirring]

979
01:06:37,086 --> 01:06:38,576
[Receiver hangs up]

980
01:06:43,259 --> 01:06:45,193
After room,
get the chief to pick up.

981
01:06:45,261 --> 01:06:46,853
[Static]

982
01:06:46,930 --> 01:06:48,727
Hoag!

983
01:06:48,798 --> 01:06:51,858
[Static]

984
01:06:51,935 --> 01:06:54,062
Maneuvering room, respond.

985
01:06:54,137 --> 01:06:55,126
[Static]

986
01:07:00,843 --> 01:07:04,074
Anybody, contact control.

987
01:07:04,147 --> 01:07:07,981
[Static]

988
01:07:14,057 --> 01:07:16,890
[Static volume increases]

989
01:07:30,006 --> 01:07:32,839
- [Clicks]
- Mr. Loomis, where's our crew?

990
01:07:34,844 --> 01:07:36,607
It's warm.

991
01:07:36,679 --> 01:07:38,943
[Creaks]

992
01:07:39,015 --> 01:07:41,176
[Wind whistling]

993
01:07:45,755 --> 01:07:48,417
[Breathes deeply]

994
01:08:14,050 --> 01:08:15,847
[Breathes deeply]

995
01:08:15,918 --> 01:08:17,180
- [Loud bang]
- [Gasps]

996
01:08:17,253 --> 01:08:20,552
[Clicking]

997
01:08:20,623 --> 01:08:21,954
[Tapping]

998
01:08:38,908 --> 01:08:41,342
[Sizzling]

999
01:08:44,314 --> 01:08:46,339
[Ticking]

1000
01:09:20,249 --> 01:09:21,546
Loomis...

1001
01:09:23,319 --> 01:09:25,253
I... I, um...

1002
01:09:25,321 --> 01:09:27,084
[Clears throat]
Go ahead.

1003
01:09:27,156 --> 01:09:29,317
I'm gonna change up my scrub.

1004
01:09:29,392 --> 01:09:32,384
Keep looking.
Gotta be somebody.

1005
01:09:32,462 --> 01:09:34,794
[Coughing]

1006
01:09:34,864 --> 01:09:37,196
[Breathes deeply]

1007
01:09:39,035 --> 01:09:40,969
[Electricity crackling]

1008
01:09:41,037 --> 01:09:43,198
[Creaking]

1009
01:09:58,755 --> 01:10:00,746
[Metal jingles]

1010
01:10:06,896 --> 01:10:09,729
[Scraping]

1011
01:10:12,368 --> 01:10:15,963
[Electricity crackling]

1012
01:10:21,811 --> 01:10:24,974
[Slow knocking]

1013
01:10:27,850 --> 01:10:30,751
[Labored breathing,
groaning]

1014
01:10:30,820 --> 01:10:33,414
All right.
All right, chief.

1015
01:10:33,489 --> 01:10:36,287
- We found you.
- Don't...

1016
01:10:36,359 --> 01:10:37,951
Can you feel anything...

1017
01:10:38,027 --> 01:10:40,518
your legs, your toes,
anything at all?

1018
01:10:40,596 --> 01:10:42,587
- Don't...
- Come on.

1019
01:10:42,665 --> 01:10:43,825
Try to stop me.

1020
01:10:43,900 --> 01:10:45,333
You're gonna pull through.

1021
01:10:45,401 --> 01:10:47,335
Especially...

1022
01:10:47,403 --> 01:10:49,462
- [Gasping]
- You.

1023
01:10:49,539 --> 01:10:51,029
[Inhales sharply]

1024
01:10:53,109 --> 01:10:55,304
[Gasps, screams]

1025
01:10:55,378 --> 01:10:57,642
Time to go.
Battery's still working.

1026
01:10:57,713 --> 01:10:59,271
[Electricity crackling]

1027
01:11:01,918 --> 01:11:03,044
[Clicking]

1028
01:11:03,119 --> 01:11:04,984
[Creaks]

1029
01:11:05,054 --> 01:11:08,785
[Both gasping]

1030
01:11:08,858 --> 01:11:10,223
What happened?

1031
01:11:10,293 --> 01:11:11,783
What happened?

1032
01:11:12,628 --> 01:11:14,220
Sparks... the hydrogen.

1033
01:11:14,297 --> 01:11:16,026
Everybody... everybody's...

1034
01:11:19,235 --> 01:11:20,497
Loomis...

1035
01:11:20,570 --> 01:11:22,401
[Breathes deeply]

1036
01:11:33,850 --> 01:11:35,681
[Exhales sharply]

1037
01:11:44,360 --> 01:11:46,851
[Breathes deeply]

1038
01:11:48,197 --> 01:11:50,688
[Screams]

1039
01:11:53,102 --> 01:11:54,865
Loomis?

1040
01:11:54,937 --> 01:11:57,565
[Grunting]

1041
01:11:57,640 --> 01:11:59,232
- Sir! Sir!
- Get out of my way!

1042
01:11:59,308 --> 01:12:01,538
- Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa.
- Get the fuck off me!

1043
01:12:01,611 --> 01:12:03,010
[Grunts]

1044
01:12:03,079 --> 01:12:04,444
Loomis!

1045
01:12:04,514 --> 01:12:05,708
- Loom...
- [Grunts]

1046
01:12:05,781 --> 01:12:07,214
[Panting]

1047
01:12:08,985 --> 01:12:10,509
He's here.

1048
01:12:19,495 --> 01:12:22,123
[Clicking]

1049
01:12:25,768 --> 01:12:26,962
[Grunts]

1050
01:12:27,036 --> 01:12:28,526
[Clicking, creaks]

1051
01:12:51,661 --> 01:12:52,889
[Rumbling]

1052
01:12:52,962 --> 01:12:54,293
Did he even have...

1053
01:12:54,363 --> 01:12:56,456
[Creaking]

1054
01:12:56,532 --> 01:12:58,466
Air?

1055
01:13:07,476 --> 01:13:09,137
[Thud]

1056
01:13:09,211 --> 01:13:12,374
[Rumbling]

1057
01:13:15,384 --> 01:13:16,817
[Water bubbling]

1058
01:13:16,886 --> 01:13:18,183
[Creaking]

1059
01:13:20,089 --> 01:13:22,580
[Rattling]

1060
01:14:04,567 --> 01:14:06,034
[Electricity crackles]

1061
01:14:30,324 --> 01:14:33,760
[Squeaks]

1062
01:14:33,828 --> 01:14:35,591
Not a bloody foot.

1063
01:14:35,663 --> 01:14:38,826
[Grunting]

1064
01:14:38,899 --> 01:14:40,230
Come on, Stumbo.
Keep trying.

1065
01:14:40,301 --> 01:14:42,997
We gotta release that air.
Come on. One more.

1066
01:14:45,506 --> 01:14:46,598
Come on, Stumbo.

1067
01:14:46,674 --> 01:14:48,437
STUMBO:
It's like it's welded.

1068
01:14:48,509 --> 01:14:49,601
[Sighs]

1069
01:14:49,677 --> 01:14:53,272
All I know is what Coors
told me.

1070
01:14:53,347 --> 01:14:54,939
And apparently...

1071
01:14:55,016 --> 01:14:59,453
Captain Winters wanted to shoot
the German survivors.

1072
01:14:59,520 --> 01:15:01,454
Mr. Brice and Mr. Loomis

1073
01:15:01,522 --> 01:15:06,289
and Mr... Mr. Coors...
wanted to help.

1074
01:15:06,360 --> 01:15:09,261
Apparently Captain Winters
lost the argument.

1075
01:15:09,330 --> 01:15:11,855
Well, that's interesting.

1076
01:15:11,932 --> 01:15:13,695
[Breathes deeply]

1077
01:15:13,768 --> 01:15:18,467
But it's not what I heard...
from Mr. Brice.

1078
01:15:20,841 --> 01:15:23,776
[Breathlessly]
Lieutenant?

1079
01:15:23,844 --> 01:15:26,608
Are you sure he came back here?

1080
01:15:26,681 --> 01:15:28,114
BRICE: Looking for me?

1081
01:15:28,182 --> 01:15:29,945
[Gasps]

1082
01:15:30,017 --> 01:15:32,485
I, uh...

1083
01:15:32,553 --> 01:15:37,149
Just... reporting, sir,
that the heating is down.

1084
01:15:37,224 --> 01:15:40,557
And, uh...
the bow's levers are stuck.

1085
01:15:40,661 --> 01:15:42,424
Stumbo's working on it
right now.

1086
01:15:42,496 --> 01:15:44,225
And that we show
90 pounds of compressed air

1087
01:15:44,298 --> 01:15:47,734
still left in the system,
and I... wasn't sure

1088
01:15:47,802 --> 01:15:50,669
if you wanted to use that
when we tried to surface

1089
01:15:50,738 --> 01:15:52,672
or use it now
so we can breathe.

1090
01:15:52,740 --> 01:15:54,605
Shinola.

1091
01:15:56,043 --> 01:15:57,237
Sir?

1092
01:15:57,311 --> 01:16:00,474
Running out of shinola, too.

1093
01:16:06,420 --> 01:16:10,447
We also wanted to ask you
about Captain Winters...

1094
01:16:10,524 --> 01:16:12,958
whether there was anything
you could tell us

1095
01:16:13,027 --> 01:16:14,517
about what happened that night

1096
01:16:14,595 --> 01:16:16,358
that might help us
to understand...

1097
01:16:16,430 --> 01:16:19,763
Don't pretend you don't know.

1098
01:16:19,834 --> 01:16:22,428
Just don't pretend anymore.

1099
01:16:28,843 --> 01:16:30,640
Well, wasn't that awkward?

1100
01:16:30,711 --> 01:16:34,613
STUMBO: Maybe Hoag was right.
Maybe we already bought it.

1101
01:16:34,682 --> 01:16:40,018
If not the depth charge,
then... the hydrogen.

1102
01:16:40,087 --> 01:16:41,952
If not the hydrogen, then...

1103
01:16:42,022 --> 01:16:43,956
[Shudders]
Maybe the cold.

1104
01:16:44,024 --> 01:16:45,184
And if not that,

1105
01:16:45,259 --> 01:16:48,524
then we got a big evil spirit
batting cleanup.

1106
01:16:48,596 --> 01:16:51,190
- Jesus Christ.
- Come on, Stumbo.

1107
01:16:51,265 --> 01:16:54,325
There should only be
so many ways a guy can die.

1108
01:16:54,401 --> 01:16:56,460
Listen to me.
CO2 hangs low.

1109
01:16:56,537 --> 01:16:59,370
It starts from the floor up,
and I need you right now...

1110
01:16:59,440 --> 01:17:01,032
- No, no.
- To get up on your feet.

1111
01:17:01,108 --> 01:17:03,133
- Maybe I just need to...
- Stumbo. Stumbo!

1112
01:17:03,210 --> 01:17:05,474
- Let me try.
- We already bought it.

1113
01:17:05,546 --> 01:17:07,036
Come on, Stumbo. Head up.

1114
01:17:07,114 --> 01:17:09,048
- Over and over...
- I need you to sit up.

1115
01:17:09,116 --> 01:17:11,016
- Over and over again.
- Look at me.

1116
01:17:11,085 --> 01:17:12,575
Now look at me.
Look at me.

1117
01:17:12,653 --> 01:17:14,245
- [Panting]
- Good.

1118
01:17:15,956 --> 01:17:17,423
Feel that?

1119
01:17:17,491 --> 01:17:19,322
Well, you're alive, then,
aren't you?

1120
01:17:19,393 --> 01:17:20,883
You fuckin'...

1121
01:17:20,961 --> 01:17:22,929
- Stumbo...
- Whoa, hey, hey, hey! Hey!

1122
01:17:22,997 --> 01:17:25,488
- Take it easy! Hey!
- Relax, man!

1123
01:17:25,566 --> 01:17:27,329
Stumbo!

1124
01:17:27,401 --> 01:17:30,336
Isn't there a winch or a pulley

1125
01:17:30,404 --> 01:17:32,497
or maybe a come-along
in a bowsman's locker?

1126
01:17:32,573 --> 01:17:33,665
- Yeah.
- Can't we use that?

1127
01:17:33,741 --> 01:17:35,174
You know what he's
talking about, Stumbo?

1128
01:17:35,242 --> 01:17:36,641
- Yeah.
- Well, come on.

1129
01:17:36,710 --> 01:17:39,201
Come... we need it. Come on.
Show... show me, Stumbo.

1130
01:17:39,280 --> 01:17:41,373
We've got to get it.
Okay, come on. Come on.

1131
01:17:41,448 --> 01:17:44,849
[Panting]

1132
01:17:44,919 --> 01:17:47,285
So, tell me
why three officers

1133
01:17:47,354 --> 01:17:50,346
would conspire to kill
their captain

1134
01:17:50,424 --> 01:17:52,688
and cover it up.

1135
01:17:52,760 --> 01:17:54,921
That's what you're thinking,
isn't it?

1136
01:17:54,995 --> 01:17:56,587
[Panting]
What if I am?

1137
01:17:56,664 --> 01:17:58,859
I can see I'm not the only one.

1138
01:18:01,435 --> 01:18:04,029
Loomis was up
for a major citation.

1139
01:18:04,104 --> 01:18:06,072
And Brice was ready
for his own command.

1140
01:18:06,140 --> 01:18:08,472
He was from a naval family.
He went to Annapolis.

1141
01:18:08,542 --> 01:18:11,010
Coors had this beautiful girl
waiting for him back in Boston

1142
01:18:11,078 --> 01:18:12,841
that he was always
talking about, Claire.

1143
01:18:12,913 --> 01:18:15,404
These guys had everything
to live for.

1144
01:18:15,482 --> 01:18:19,976
By that reasoning...
they had everything to lose.

1145
01:18:20,054 --> 01:18:22,545
[Soft rumbling]

1146
01:18:26,026 --> 01:18:28,290
Are we missing somebody?

1147
01:18:28,362 --> 01:18:30,193
[Rumbling continues]

1148
01:18:44,879 --> 01:18:46,369
Wallace...

1149
01:18:48,449 --> 01:18:49,939
Wallace?

1150
01:18:51,518 --> 01:18:52,485
- No!
- [Gasps]

1151
01:18:52,553 --> 01:18:54,077
- No! No!
- Shh!

1152
01:18:54,154 --> 01:18:56,520
- No-o-o!
- It's just us.

1153
01:18:56,590 --> 01:18:58,615
It's just... us.

1154
01:18:58,692 --> 01:19:01,286
- [All panting]
- Now, listen...

1155
01:19:01,362 --> 01:19:03,853
We're running out of plays
in the playbook.

1156
01:19:03,931 --> 01:19:06,695
Do you have... any idea
why the boat is going back

1157
01:19:06,767 --> 01:19:09,634
or how we can get control
of it?

1158
01:19:09,703 --> 01:19:10,795
[Panting]

1159
01:19:10,871 --> 01:19:13,032
I've been checking the
literature on this subject.

1160
01:19:13,107 --> 01:19:15,371
And the thing we know
about maledictions is...

1161
01:19:15,442 --> 01:19:16,534
Maledictions?

1162
01:19:16,610 --> 01:19:17,770
Look it up.

1163
01:19:17,845 --> 01:19:20,075
Maledictions don't issue
from Heaven or Hell

1164
01:19:20,147 --> 01:19:22,638
but from some unresolved place
in between.

1165
01:19:22,716 --> 01:19:24,343
In fact, there's a great...

1166
01:19:24,418 --> 01:19:26,682
Wallace...
we're running out of air.

1167
01:19:26,754 --> 01:19:28,688
[Breathes deeply]

1168
01:19:28,756 --> 01:19:31,691
Suffice to say...

1169
01:19:31,759 --> 01:19:36,287
the malediction needs
satisfaction

1170
01:19:36,363 --> 01:19:39,127
in order to escape
its netherworld.

1171
01:19:39,199 --> 01:19:41,963
And if you had to guess...

1172
01:19:42,036 --> 01:19:45,631
what would satisfy
our malediction?

1173
01:19:45,706 --> 01:19:47,731
Old Man Winters never
got a chance

1174
01:19:47,808 --> 01:19:49,298
to go down with the ship,
did he?

1175
01:19:51,145 --> 01:19:52,407
[Creaking]

1176
01:19:52,479 --> 01:19:54,811
[Labored breathing]

1177
01:19:57,184 --> 01:19:58,310
[Grunts]

1178
01:19:58,385 --> 01:19:59,818
Wallace, leave yours here.

1179
01:19:59,887 --> 01:20:02,014
We gotta dig up
some more light.

1180
01:20:02,089 --> 01:20:03,420
Okay, listen, uh...

1181
01:20:03,490 --> 01:20:07,824
Just... Just promise me
you'll stay on your feet, okay?

1182
01:20:10,664 --> 01:20:12,757
[Breathes deeply]

1183
01:20:20,440 --> 01:20:22,203
"Don't pretend..."

1184
01:20:22,275 --> 01:20:28,942
"Don't pretend
you don't... know."

1185
01:20:30,717 --> 01:20:32,207
[Metal jingling]

1186
01:20:43,797 --> 01:20:46,459
[Heavy breathing]

1187
01:20:54,507 --> 01:20:56,668
[Shuddering]

1188
01:21:05,118 --> 01:21:06,710
- [Loud bang]
- [Gasping]

1189
01:21:21,034 --> 01:21:22,695
[Breathes deeply]

1190
01:21:44,891 --> 01:21:47,052
BRICE:
2230 hours: Sight target

1191
01:21:47,127 --> 01:21:48,822
believed to be
German sub tender.

1192
01:21:48,895 --> 01:21:51,591
Winters orders flank speed
to close target

1193
01:21:51,665 --> 01:21:53,633
and gain a firing angle.

1194
01:21:53,700 --> 01:21:56,828
2315: Loomis checks
target profile against I.D. log,

1195
01:21:56,903 --> 01:22:00,896
matching it to target, and
I personally verify the match.

1196
01:22:02,008 --> 01:22:06,468
2320: Single torpedo fired
from number-4 tube.

1197
01:22:07,647 --> 01:22:08,773
[Explosion]

1198
01:22:08,848 --> 01:22:13,182
Heard the strike, followed by
collapsing bulkheads.

1199
01:22:13,253 --> 01:22:16,689
2330 hours: To confirm sinking
of German ship,

1200
01:22:16,756 --> 01:22:18,781
four officers go topside...

1201
01:22:18,858 --> 01:22:21,952
Commander Winters,
myself, Lieutenant Loomis,

1202
01:22:22,028 --> 01:22:24,189
and Lieutenant
J.G. Stephen Coors.

1203
01:22:24,264 --> 01:22:26,528
PAGE:
"Many bodies in the water."

1204
01:22:26,599 --> 01:22:28,533
[Explosion]

1205
01:22:28,601 --> 01:22:30,796
[Indistinct shouting]

1206
01:22:30,870 --> 01:22:33,031
"Ship burning on the horizon."

1207
01:22:34,708 --> 01:22:36,175
- [Glass shatters]
- [Gasps]

1208
01:22:36,242 --> 01:22:39,006
[Heavy breathing]

1209
01:23:14,781 --> 01:23:16,874
[Panting]

1210
01:23:32,399 --> 01:23:34,196
[Shuddering]

1211
01:23:40,974 --> 01:23:42,532
[Curtain opens]

1212
01:23:42,609 --> 01:23:45,373
[Heavy breathing]

1213
01:23:45,445 --> 01:23:48,278
[Slow footsteps]

1214
01:23:53,453 --> 01:23:56,286
[Footsteps approaching]

1215
01:24:01,428 --> 01:24:04,522
[Footsteps departing]

1216
01:24:04,597 --> 01:24:06,360
[Silence]

1217
01:24:06,433 --> 01:24:08,094
[Flashlight clicks]

1218
01:24:24,784 --> 01:24:26,376
[Screams]

1219
01:24:27,153 --> 01:24:29,747
[Chuckles]

1220
01:24:29,823 --> 01:24:31,950
What are you doing in here?

1221
01:24:33,960 --> 01:24:34,892
Go.

1222
01:24:34,961 --> 01:24:37,486
[Rattling]

1223
01:24:37,564 --> 01:24:38,496
[Clicks]

1224
01:24:38,565 --> 01:24:40,328
[Shuddering]
A German ship...

1225
01:24:40,400 --> 01:24:42,732
of the type
Brice said you sunk.

1226
01:24:44,370 --> 01:24:49,069
My ship...
the Fort James hospital ship.

1227
01:24:49,142 --> 01:24:51,736
[Shuddering]
So what you're saying is...

1228
01:24:51,811 --> 01:24:55,269
that the submarine
Kingsley saw...

1229
01:24:55,348 --> 01:24:57,942
the one
he thought was German...

1230
01:24:58,017 --> 01:24:59,348
Wasn't.

1231
01:25:02,422 --> 01:25:03,650
So it was an accident?

1232
01:25:03,723 --> 01:25:06,419
Not when he left us
in the water to die.

1233
01:25:06,493 --> 01:25:09,656
Not when he heard the cries
for help in English.

1234
01:25:09,729 --> 01:25:10,661
You actually believe

1235
01:25:10,730 --> 01:25:12,857
that Captain Winters would
just leave...

1236
01:25:12,932 --> 01:25:15,423
PAGE: Help! Help me!

1237
01:25:15,502 --> 01:25:17,094
O'DELL: No.

1238
01:25:17,170 --> 01:25:20,833
Captain Winters wanted to
pick up the survivors.

1239
01:25:21,875 --> 01:25:22,807
That means...

1240
01:25:22,876 --> 01:25:25,140
PAGE: Help!

1241
01:25:29,883 --> 01:25:31,851
Who mis-I.D.'d the ship?

1242
01:25:33,386 --> 01:25:35,718
Who had everything to lose?

1243
01:25:44,464 --> 01:25:46,932
[Creaking, rumbling]

1244
01:25:55,274 --> 01:25:58,368
Either the battery has
finally crapped out, or...

1245
01:25:58,444 --> 01:26:00,173
Or maybe we're here.

1246
01:26:08,955 --> 01:26:11,014
Come on.
Let's get some air going.

1247
01:26:12,291 --> 01:26:14,555
- [Clicking]
- All right.

1248
01:26:14,627 --> 01:26:16,424
Come on, everybody, pull!
Come on!

1249
01:26:16,496 --> 01:26:18,054
- [Clicking]
- [Grunting]

1250
01:26:18,130 --> 01:26:20,428
[Grunting]

1251
01:26:20,500 --> 01:26:22,331
Come on! Pull!

1252
01:26:22,401 --> 01:26:24,426
[Loud banging]

1253
01:26:27,240 --> 01:26:29,231
[Creaking]

1254
01:26:31,244 --> 01:26:33,178
Fuck me. This is it.

1255
01:26:33,246 --> 01:26:35,544
- Oh!
- God, I hate being right.

1256
01:26:35,615 --> 01:26:37,879
[All panting, grunting]

1257
01:26:37,950 --> 01:26:39,508
- Pull!
- [Creaking]

1258
01:26:45,358 --> 01:26:46,290
[Thud]

1259
01:26:46,359 --> 01:26:48,919
[Grunting]

1260
01:26:51,631 --> 01:26:53,428
- [Air whooshing]
- [Grunts]

1261
01:26:58,137 --> 01:26:59,399
Kingsley.

1262
01:26:59,472 --> 01:27:01,463
[Creaking]

1263
01:27:01,541 --> 01:27:02,803
Oh, Jesus, God,
we're going down.

1264
01:27:02,875 --> 01:27:05,207
[Grunting, panting]

1265
01:27:05,278 --> 01:27:06,870
[Squeaking]

1266
01:27:06,946 --> 01:27:09,039
[Creaking]

1267
01:27:09,115 --> 01:27:10,844
It's going up.

1268
01:27:10,917 --> 01:27:11,975
It's going up!

1269
01:27:13,419 --> 01:27:16,411
[Whirring]

1270
01:27:28,367 --> 01:27:31,165
[Panting]

1271
01:27:35,741 --> 01:27:39,507
[Indistinct shouting]

1272
01:27:42,582 --> 01:27:45,949
[Rumbling]

1273
01:27:48,854 --> 01:27:50,344
[Flashlight clicks]

1274
01:27:52,491 --> 01:27:54,254
[Groans]

1275
01:27:54,327 --> 01:27:55,589
[All panting]

1276
01:27:55,661 --> 01:27:56,992
[Flashlight clicks]

1277
01:28:06,539 --> 01:28:09,702
- [Electricity crackles]
- Okay. All right.

1278
01:28:09,775 --> 01:28:13,370
Wallace, see if you can work the
radar, get a sweep of the area.

1279
01:28:13,446 --> 01:28:15,778
Stumbo, see if you can crack
this hatch. Use a crowbar.

1280
01:28:15,848 --> 01:28:17,839
Drain the tower.
See if we can get out that way.

1281
01:28:17,917 --> 01:28:19,612
If not, we gotta go out
the forward...

1282
01:28:28,461 --> 01:28:31,453
[Shuddering]

1283
01:28:33,299 --> 01:28:35,164
Oh, God.

1284
01:28:37,203 --> 01:28:39,535
Hey, fellas...
we have contact.

1285
01:28:39,605 --> 01:28:42,699
On SJ radar...
4,000 yards, starboard beam.

1286
01:28:45,745 --> 01:28:48,339
It's the same one?
It's the same kraut ship?

1287
01:28:48,414 --> 01:28:50,974
- Are we being choosy?
- All right.

1288
01:28:51,050 --> 01:28:52,642
Uh, Wallace, raise the antenna.

1289
01:28:52,718 --> 01:28:54,447
Issue a radio challenge
on the Ariel-6.

1290
01:28:54,520 --> 01:28:55,953
Get the ship I.D.'d
as of right now.

1291
01:28:56,022 --> 01:28:57,683
BRICE:
Well done, Mr. O'Dell.

1292
01:29:05,030 --> 01:29:07,021
But I'm feeling
much better now.

1293
01:29:20,579 --> 01:29:22,911
You were saying?

1294
01:29:22,982 --> 01:29:24,643
We have a contact.

1295
01:29:26,118 --> 01:29:27,779
That may be an opportunity.

1296
01:29:27,853 --> 01:29:29,753
An opportunity?

1297
01:29:30,823 --> 01:29:32,188
To abandon ship.

1298
01:29:32,258 --> 01:29:35,125
Well, I don't know that
that's a friendly out there.

1299
01:29:35,194 --> 01:29:36,286
Well, neither do I.

1300
01:29:36,362 --> 01:29:38,557
But it seems better to scuttle
now and take our chances

1301
01:29:38,631 --> 01:29:40,462
with a surface vessel,
even if it is German.

1302
01:29:40,532 --> 01:29:42,227
Scuttle and tell Connecticut
what?

1303
01:29:42,301 --> 01:29:44,735
We sunk one of their
finest fleet submarines

1304
01:29:44,803 --> 01:29:46,896
because we lost a few men
carrying out our mission?

1305
01:29:46,972 --> 01:29:48,599
A few men, sir?

1306
01:29:48,674 --> 01:29:51,074
[Creaking]

1307
01:29:51,143 --> 01:29:54,237
Contact at 2,500 yards.

1308
01:29:54,313 --> 01:29:55,575
Might cross the stern.

1309
01:29:55,648 --> 01:29:57,912
We'll wait... right here.

1310
01:30:00,819 --> 01:30:04,482
Wallace... no matter what
Mr. Brice says,

1311
01:30:04,556 --> 01:30:06,217
I want you to go
to the radio shack

1312
01:30:06,292 --> 01:30:08,954
and establish a voice contact
with that ship immediately.

1313
01:30:09,028 --> 01:30:10,393
You are not the skipper
of this ship, Mr. O'Dell!

1314
01:30:10,462 --> 01:30:12,396
And neither are you, sir!

1315
01:30:13,799 --> 01:30:15,426
[Gasps]

1316
01:30:18,470 --> 01:30:19,994
[Gunfire]

1317
01:30:20,072 --> 01:30:22,097
[Electricity crackles]

1318
01:30:26,245 --> 01:30:27,177
[Gun clicks]

1319
01:30:27,246 --> 01:30:28,406
[Thud]

1320
01:30:31,350 --> 01:30:32,612
[Clip clicks]

1321
01:30:32,685 --> 01:30:33,845
[Gun cocks]

1322
01:30:38,691 --> 01:30:40,591
[Rain falling]

1323
01:30:40,693 --> 01:30:42,524
Rain squall.

1324
01:30:44,830 --> 01:30:47,264
With a little luck, they
won't see us in all this...

1325
01:30:47,333 --> 01:30:49,494
- [Clicks]
- Weather.

1326
01:30:57,142 --> 01:30:59,269
[Thunder crashes]

1327
01:31:06,217 --> 01:31:08,378
[Thunder crashes]

1328
01:31:18,229 --> 01:31:19,560
Here!

1329
01:31:19,631 --> 01:31:21,565
Please!

1330
01:31:21,633 --> 01:31:23,225
We're over here!

1331
01:31:23,301 --> 01:31:26,236
Please!

1332
01:31:26,304 --> 01:31:28,397
Help, please!

1333
01:31:28,473 --> 01:31:30,065
Help!

1334
01:31:30,141 --> 01:31:32,371
On your starboard side!

1335
01:31:32,443 --> 01:31:34,604
[Shouts indistinctly]

1336
01:31:36,748 --> 01:31:38,340
[Thunder crashes]

1337
01:31:38,416 --> 01:31:41,146
It's really not safe up here,
Miss Page.

1338
01:31:46,357 --> 01:31:49,087
We're going below now!

1339
01:31:49,160 --> 01:31:50,593
Aah!

1340
01:31:56,167 --> 01:31:58,761
Bury everybody
and bury the truth...

1341
01:31:58,836 --> 01:32:00,326
is that it, Brice?!

1342
01:32:03,141 --> 01:32:04,904
Like this.

1343
01:32:04,976 --> 01:32:07,274
This is how I go.

1344
01:32:07,345 --> 01:32:08,573
[Grunts]

1345
01:32:09,714 --> 01:32:11,807
If that's your plan...

1346
01:32:11,883 --> 01:32:14,647
get on with it,
you fucking coward!

1347
01:32:14,719 --> 01:32:16,846
[Keys jingling,
door hinges creak]

1348
01:32:16,921 --> 01:32:18,252
[Gunshot]

1349
01:32:22,193 --> 01:32:25,458
Stumbo, man the ports.
Get ready to scuttle this boat!

1350
01:32:27,165 --> 01:32:28,427
Just leave!

1351
01:32:28,499 --> 01:32:30,330
They'll blame it on a U-boat!

1352
01:32:31,869 --> 01:32:34,770
Just get out of here!
They'll never fuckin' know!

1353
01:32:34,839 --> 01:32:36,602
Any more advice for me, champ?

1354
01:32:36,674 --> 01:32:38,164
[Gunshots]

1355
01:32:40,945 --> 01:32:42,276
[Gunshot]

1356
01:32:48,286 --> 01:32:49,548
[Thunder rumbling]

1357
01:32:49,621 --> 01:32:51,851
500 yards and closing!

1358
01:32:51,923 --> 01:32:53,982
Looks like we're definitely
gonna lose some paint

1359
01:32:54,058 --> 01:32:55,150
on this one, sir!

1360
01:32:55,226 --> 01:32:58,320
I kept looking for some way
just...

1361
01:32:58,396 --> 01:33:01,627
just to... take it back,

1362
01:33:01,699 --> 01:33:03,792
to make it end right...

1363
01:33:03,868 --> 01:33:07,201
some way without
dishonoring Winters.

1364
01:33:08,906 --> 01:33:11,670
[Chuckles]

1365
01:33:11,743 --> 01:33:14,906
I was gonna wear this uniform
back to port.

1366
01:33:16,281 --> 01:33:18,272
Now...

1367
01:33:24,155 --> 01:33:26,248
What should I do, Miss Page?

1368
01:33:26,324 --> 01:33:29,691
You give me the light
so that I can signal for help.

1369
01:33:29,761 --> 01:33:31,092
I don't...

1370
01:33:32,997 --> 01:33:35,022
God, I don't know!

1371
01:33:46,110 --> 01:33:49,102
[Thunder crashes]

1372
01:33:55,953 --> 01:33:57,887
[Thunder crashes]

1373
01:34:00,525 --> 01:34:03,517
[Thunder rumbling]

1374
01:34:12,103 --> 01:34:14,731
I just figured out
why he didn't kill me, too.

1375
01:34:15,773 --> 01:34:17,240
He didn't have to.

1376
01:34:18,009 --> 01:34:18,873
[Gasps]

1377
01:34:20,378 --> 01:34:22,312
[Gunshot, thunder crashes]

1378
01:34:25,883 --> 01:34:26,975
[Gunshot]

1379
01:34:36,361 --> 01:34:39,797
Aah!

1380
01:34:57,215 --> 01:34:59,046
[Thunder crashes]

1381
01:35:02,653 --> 01:35:05,918
Hey! Over here!

1382
01:35:05,990 --> 01:35:07,617
Come back!

1383
01:35:07,725 --> 01:35:10,489
[Voice breaking]
Come back.

1384
01:35:12,497 --> 01:35:14,431
[Thunder crashes]

1385
01:35:14,499 --> 01:35:16,490
[Panting]

1386
01:35:19,370 --> 01:35:20,997
[Panting]

1387
01:35:21,939 --> 01:35:23,304
[Exhales sharply]

1388
01:35:50,401 --> 01:35:53,393
[Rattling]

1389
01:36:11,522 --> 01:36:14,013
[Exhales deeply]

1390
01:36:16,294 --> 01:36:21,231
Well, you weren't the first
woman that ever slapped me,

1391
01:36:21,299 --> 01:36:23,392
and you won't be the last.

1392
01:36:23,468 --> 01:36:26,528
But that was a good thing
you done for me back there.

1393
01:36:28,439 --> 01:36:29,770
Well done, Miss Page.

1394
01:36:32,944 --> 01:36:35,708
Well done, Mr. Stumbo.

1395
01:36:37,682 --> 01:36:40,515
Dead but not buried, I see.

1396
01:36:43,621 --> 01:36:44,588
Pardon me?

1397
01:36:44,655 --> 01:36:46,350
Your vessel.

1398
01:36:46,424 --> 01:36:49,757
[Creaking, rumbling]

1399
01:37:05,943 --> 01:37:09,777
[Water splashing]

1400
01:37:17,421 --> 01:37:21,915
So, what would you say
if you had to explain it all?

1401
01:37:22,994 --> 01:37:25,656
Does seem rather unlikely now,
doesn't it?

1402
01:37:28,733 --> 01:37:30,997
Have you thought that...

1403
01:37:31,068 --> 01:37:33,002
that maybe
when Captain Winters died,

1404
01:37:33,070 --> 01:37:36,836
he just... died, and that was it?

1405
01:37:36,908 --> 01:37:38,842
And the rest...

1406
01:37:38,910 --> 01:37:40,377
[Exhales deeply]

1407
01:37:40,444 --> 01:37:42,412
And the rest...

1408
01:37:43,915 --> 01:37:45,246
I don't know.

1409
01:37:48,386 --> 01:37:51,378
You say whatever
you have to say, ensign.

1410
01:37:52,623 --> 01:37:56,457
I'll always believe we were
brought back here for a reason.

1411
01:38:02,233 --> 01:38:04,724
[Rumbling]

1412
01:38:31,796 --> 01:38:34,797
[Suspenseful instrumental music
plays]

1413
01:45:15,732 --> 01:45:18,360
[Music ends]

